// 1. Explain all the CSS positions(static, fixed, sticky, relative, absolute) with one code example each.

1 Static:

Static positioning is the default position value for elements.
Elements with position: static; are positioned according to the normal flow of the document.

Examples

// HTML
<div class="box">Static</div>

// CSS
.box {
  position: static;
  width: 200px;
  height: 200px;
  background-color: red;
}

2 Fixed:

Fixed positioning positions an element relative to the viewport, so it remains fixed even when scrolling.

Example:

// HTML

<div class="box">Fixed</div>

// CSS

.box {
  position: fixed;
  top: 50px;
  right: 50px;
  width: 200px;
  height: 200px;
  background-color: blue;
}

3 Sticky:

Sticky positioning is a mix of relative and fixed positioning. It acts as relative until a specific scroll threshold is reached, then it becomes fixed.

Example:

//HTML
<div class="container">
  <div class="box">Sticky</div>
</div>

// CSS

.container {
  height: 500px;
  overflow-y: scroll;
}

.box {
  position: sticky;
  top: 50px;
  width: 200px;
  height: 200px;
  background-color: green;
}

4 Relative:

Relative positioning positions an element relative to its normal position.

Example:

// HTML
<div class="box">Relative</div>

// CSS
.box {
  position: relative;
  top: 20px;
  left: 20px;
  width: 200px;
  height: 200px;
  background-color: orange;
}

5 Absolute:

Absolute positioning positions an element relative to its closest positioned ancestor or the initial containing block (viewport if no ancestor is positioned).

Example:
// HTML

<div class="container">
  <div class="box">Absolute</div>
</div>

// CSS

.container {
  position: relative;
  width: 300px;
  height: 300px;
}

.box {
  position: absolute;
  top: 50px;
  left: 50px;
  width: 200px;
  height: 200px;
  background-color: yellow;
}





























